[0.005, "o", "\u001b[H\u001b[0;10;4;1m\u000f\u001b[96m[\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[96mPHP\u001b[0;10;4;1m\u000f\u001b[96m]\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[35X\r\n\u001b[27X\n;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[4;3HAbout php.ini   ;\u001b[46X\u001b[5;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[43X\u001b[6;3HPHP's initialization file, generally called php.ini, is responsible for\u001b[7;3Hconfiguring many of the aspects of PHP's behavior.\u001b[11X\r\n\u001b[68X\u001b[9;3HPHP attempts to find and load this configuration from a number of locations.\u001b[10;2H The following is a summary of its search order:\r\n; 1. SAPI module specific location.\u001b[12;2H 2. The PHPRC environment variable.\u001b[13;3H3. A number of predefined registry keys on Windows\u001b[14;2H 4. Current working directory (except CLI)\r\n; 5. The web server's directory (for SAPI modules), or directory of PHP\u001b[16;3H(otherwise in Windows)\u001b[50X\u001b[17;3H6. The directory from the --with-config-file-path compile time option, or the\u001b[18;2H Windows directory (usually C:\\windows)\u001b[19;3HSee the PHP docs for more specific information.\u001b[20;2H https://php.net/configuration.file\r\n\u001b[14X\u001b[22;2H The syntax of the file is extremely simple.  Whitespace and lines\u001b[23;3Hbeginning with a semicolon are silently ignored (as you probably guessed).\u001b[24;2H Section headers (e.g. [Foo]) are also silently ignored, even though\u001b[25;3Hthey might mean something in the future.\u001b[34X\r\n\u001b[66X\u001b[27;2H Directives following the section heading [PATH=/www/mysite] only\u001b[28;3Happly to PHP files in the /www/mysite directory.  Directives\u001b[29;2H following the section heading [HOST=www.example.com] only apply to\u001b[30;3HPHP files served from www.example.com.  Directives set in these\u001b[10X\u001b[31;3Hspecial sections cannot be overridden by user-defined INI files or    \u001b[32;3Hat runtime. Currently, [PATH=] and [HOST=] sections only work under\u001b[6X\u001b[33;3HCGI/FastCGI.\u001b[30X\u001b[34;2H https://php.net/ini.sections\r\n\u001b[17X\u001b[36;2H Directives are specified using the following syntax:\u001b[37;2H directive = value\r\n; Directive names are *case sensitive* - foo=bar is different from FOO=bar.\u001b[39;2H Directives are variables used to configure PHP or PHP extensions.\u001b[40;2H There is no name validation.  If PHP can't find an expected\u001b[41;2H directive because it is not set or is mistyped, a default value will be used.\r\n\u001b[14X\u001b[43;2H The value can be a string, a number, a PHP constant (e.g. E_ALL or M_PI), one\u001b[44;2H of the INI constants (On, Off, True, False, Yes, No and None) or an expression\u001b[45;2H (e.g. E_ALL & ~E_NOTICE), a quoted string (\"bar\"), or a reference to a\u001b[46;2H previously set variable or directive (e.g. ${foo})\u001b[47;153H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f1,1            Top\u001b[48;17H\u001b[?25h"]
[0.973, "o", "\u001b[?25l\b\u001b[m\u000f \b"]
[0.004, "o", "\u001b[H; https://php.net/default-socket-timeout\r\ndefault_socket_timeout = 60\r\n\u001b[19X\u001b[4;3HIf your scripts have to deal with files from Macintosh systems,\u001b[5;2H or you are running on a Mac and need to deal with files from\u001b[6;3Hunix or win32 systems, setting this flag will cause PHP to\u001b[13X\u001b[7;3Hautomatically detect the EOL character in those files so that\r\n; fgets() and file() will work regardless of the source of the file.\u001b[9;3Hhttps://php.net/auto-detect-line-endings\u001b[36X\u001b[10;2Hauto_detect_line_endings = Off\u001b[18X\r\n\u001b[35X\u001b[12;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[14X\u001b[13;3HDynamic Extensions ;\u001b[30X\u001b[14;2H;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;;\u001b[21X\r\n\u001b[71X\u001b[16;3HIf you wish to have an extension loaded automatically, use the following\u001b[17;3Hsyntax:\u001b[70X\u001b[18;2H\u001b[39X\u001b[19;3H  extension=modulename\u001b[25X\u001b[20;2H\u001b[35X\r\n; For example:\u001b[22;2H\u001b[66X\u001b[23;3H  \u001b[30m\u001b[103mextension=mysq\u001b[m\u000fli\u001b[56X\u001b[24;2H\u001b[68X\u001b[25;3HWhen the extension library to load is not located in the default extension\r\n; directory, You may specify an absolute path to the library file:\u001b[27;2H\u001b[65X\u001b[28;3H  extension=/path/to/extension/mysqli.so\u001b[20X\u001b[29;2H\u001b[67X\u001b[30;3HNote : The syntax used in previous PHP versions ('extension=<ext>.so' and\u001b[31;3H'extension='php_<ext>.dll') is supported for legacy reasons and may be\u001b[32;3Hdeprecated in a future PHP major version. So, when it is possible, please\u001b[33;3Hmove to the new ('extension=<ext>) syntax.\u001b[34;2H\u001b[29X\r\n;extension=bcmath\u001b[36;2Hextension=bz2\u001b[40X\u001b[37;2Hextension=calendar\r\nextension=\u001b[92mcurl\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[61X\u001b[39;2Hextension=dba\u001b[53X\u001b[40;2Hextension=enchant\u001b[43X\u001b[41;2Hextension=exif\u001b[64X\r\n;extension=ffi\u001b[43;2Hextension=ftp\u001b[65X\u001b[44;2Hextension=gd\u001b[67X\u001b[45;2Hextension=gettext\u001b[54X\u001b[46;2Hextension=gmp\u001b[38X\u001b[47;153H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f900,5          47%\u001b[48;16H\u001b[?25h"]
