[0.007, "o", "\u001b[1;2H\u001b[33X\r\n# Configuration and logfile names: If the filenames you specify for many\u001b[3;3Hof the server's control files begin with \"/\" (or \"drive:/\" for Win32), the\r\n# server will use that explicit path.  If the filenames do *not* begin\r\n# with \"/\", the value of ServerRoot is prepended -- so \"logs/access_log\"\u001b[6;3Hwith ServerRoot set to \"/usr/local/apache2\" will be interpreted by the\r\n# server as \"/usr/local/apache2/logs/access_log\", whereas \"/logs/access_log\" \r\n# will be interpreted as '/logs/access_log'.\r\n\u001b[11X\n#\u001b[11;5HrverRoot: The top of the directory tree under which the server's\u001b[12;2H configuration, error, and log files are kept.\u001b[14;3HDo not add a slash at the end of the directory path.  If you point\u001b[15;3HServerRoot at a non-local disk, be sure to specify a local disk on the\u001b[16;3HMutex directive, if file-based mutexes are used.  If you wish to share the\u001b[17;2H same ServerRoot for multiple httpd daemons, you will need to change at\r\n# least PidFile.\u001b[5X\r\n#\u001b[28X\n\u001b[96merverRoot\u001b[m\u000f \u001b[92m\"/etc/httpd\"\u001b[m\u000f\u001b[6X\r\n\u001b[11X\n#\r\n# Mutex: \u001b[30m\u001b[103mAl\u001b[m\u000flows you to set the mutex mechanism and mutex file directory\r\n# for individual mutexes, or change the global defaults\r\n#\u001b[20X\r\n# Uncomment and change the directory if mutexes are file-based and the default\r\n# mutex file directory is not on a local disk or is not appropriate for some\r\n# other reason.\u001b[K\r\n#\u001b[K\r\n# Mutex default:/run/httpd\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n#\u001b[K\r\n# Listen: \u001b[30m\u001b[103mAl\u001b[m\u000flows you to bind Apache to specific IP addresses and/or\u001b[K\r\n# ports, instead of the default. See also the <VirtualHost>\u001b[K\r\n# directive.\u001b[K\r\n#\u001b[K\r\n# Change this to Listen on specific IP addresses as shown below to \u001b[K\r\n# prevent Apache from glomming onto all bound IP addresses.\u001b[K\r\n#\u001b[K\r\n#Listen 12.34.56.78:80\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[96mListen\u001b[m\u000f 80\u001b[K\r\n\u001b[K\n#\u001b[K\r\n# Dynamic Shared Object (DSO) Support\u001b[K\r\n#\u001b[K\r\n# To be able to use the functionality of a module which was built as a DSO you\u001b[K\u001b[47;153H\u001b[0;10;7m\u000f34,10           2%\u001b[48;4H\u001b[?25h"]
